Both great questions. Let me take them one at a time, plain.

1. How are you "quietly building the doorway"?

In this project, to draw the chart, you'll build a small web address that gives back pure data (just numbers, no page). Something like:

/api/weather/   →  returns:  [{"time": "9am", "temp": 14}, {"time": "10am", "temp": 15}, ...]

Notice: no page, no design — just data. That's called an API (a data-only doorway).

Now here's the thing:
- In Design A, your own chart asks that doorway for data. ✅
- In Design B, a React/Stitch frontend would ask that exact same doorway for data. ✅

Same doorway, works for both. So the moment you build the chart's data-doorway, you've built the one thing Design B needs. That's how you're quietly making B possible without trying to.

2. Do Django's auto-built tables become useless in B?

No — most of them stay useful. Common misconception, good catch.

Remember: the database + tables belong to the engine, and in B the engine stays. So:

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                      Table                      │                 In Design B?                  │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ weather_weatherreading, weather_otpcode (yours) │ ✅ Still used — your data lives here          │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ auth_user (the users)                           │ ✅ Still used — users are still stored here   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ django_admin_log, django_content_type           │ ✅ Still used — Django admin still works in B │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ django_session                                  │ ⚠️ This one usually goes quiet                │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────┘

That last one is the real answer to your instinct. In A, login uses "sessions" → the django_session table gets used. In B, login usually switches to "tokens" instead → so django_session sits unused.

So you were half right: not all the auto-tables become useless — just the one session table tends to go quiet. Everything else (users, your data, admin) keeps working exactly the same.

The key idea: switching to B changes the face and how login is checked — but the database and its tables mostly stay put, because they belong to the engine, and the engine stays. 🙂
